	(1,1,'2014-08-04 18:14:05','2014-08-04 18:14:05','WordPress is an award-winning web software, used by millions of webmasters worldwide for building their website or blog. SiteGround is proud to host this particular WordPress installation and provide users with multiple resources to facilitate the management of their WP websites:\r\n<h3>Expert <a href=\"http://www.siteground.com/wordpress-hosting.htm\">WordPress Hosting</a></h3>\r\nSiteGround provides superior WordPress hosting focused on speed, security and customer service. We take care of WordPress sites security with unique server-level customizations, WP auto-updates, and daily backups. We make them faster by regularly upgrading our hardware, offering free CDN with Railgun and developing our SuperCacher that speeds sites up to 100 times! And last but not least, we provide real WordPress help 24/7! Learn more about SiteGround WordPress hosting\r\n<h3>Wordpress tutorial and knowledgebase articles</h3>\r\nWordPress is considered an easy to work with software. Yet, if you are a beginner you might need some help, or you might be looking for tweaks that do not come naturally even to more advanced users. SiteGround <a href=\"http://www.siteground.com/tutorials/wordpress/\">WordPress tutorial</a> includes installation and theme change instructions, management of WordPress plugins, manual upgrade and backup creation, and more. If you are looking for a more rare setup or modification, you may visit <a href=\"http://kb.siteground.com\">SiteGround Knowledgebase</a>.\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://www.siteground.com/wordpress-hosting/wordpress-themes.htm\">Free WordPress themes</a></h3>\r\nSiteGround experts not only develop various solutions for WordPress sites, but also create unique designs that you could download for free. SiteGround WordPress themes are easy to customize for the particular use of the webmaster.','WordPress Resources at SiteGround','','publish','open','open','','wordpress-resources-at-siteground','','','2014-08-04 18:14:05','2014-08-04 18:14:05','',0,'',0,'post','',0),
	(37,3,'2014-11-24 23:02:47','2014-11-24 23:02:47','<b>Ayasha J. Tripp, Executive Director/Founder</b>\r\n\r\nAyasha  is an energetic and passionate young woman who comes from the small town of Pittsburg, CA – the outskirts of the bustling San Francisco Bay Area. She\'s been writing stories since she was 7. Her passion and love for writing, film and theatre led her to pursue a degree in Television/Film New Media from San Diego State University. In her four and half years of attending SDSU she had the opportunity to study abroad in Singapore at Nanyang Technological University and study new media and film. She has written and directed two short films entitled, \'Unidentified\' and \'Bowling from Behind.\' In her last year attending SDSU, in association with the African American Student Drama Association she was granted the opportunity to produce/direct/write her first full length 3-Act play entitled, \'The Skin I’m In.\' The play was a huge success on her campus and sparked the idea for her to create Don\'t Even Tripp Productions. In the spring of 2010, her newly founded production company released her 2nd full length play \'and an Angel Came Down\' which premiered at the Lesher Center for the Arts in Walnut Creek, CA. The play was received very well, selling out the 2nd night! Half of the ticket proceeds were donated to the Youth Uprising Center of Oakland, CA.  After the production Tripp relocated to Chicago to expand her knowledge on theatre and writing. She had the opportunity to work as a Development Associate at the Writers Theatre. She was also under the mentorship of playwright Gloria Bond Clunie and Director  Chuck Smith and was granted the opportunity to work as their stage manager for the stage reading for the play <em>Smoke. </em>Ayasha has just recently graduated with her Masters in Afro American Studies  from the University of Wisconsin Madison. During her time on campus she worked closely with Patrick Sims founder of TCSA(Theatre for Culture &amp; Social Awareness) and hosted the WSUM radio show\"The Velvet Rope Radio Hour\" She has the opportunity to teach creative writing and theatre at UW Madison, Writers in Prison Project, and UC Berkeley Upward Bound Program. She is now back home in the Bay Area and is beyond ready to take Don\'t Even Tripp to the next level. \"I just want to help people tap into their purpose and passion and I believe theatre that can do that\"!\r\n\r\n<b>Asia Jackson, Literary Manager</b>\r\n\r\nAsia Jackson is an actress and avid lover of theatre who is also  from the Bay Area, CA. Upon entering college at San Diego State, she, like so many prospective and freshman college students, did not know what she wanted to do. She pre-majored in business with an emphasis in management. However, her sophomore year, she randomly auditioned in a student-written play, and was cast as the lead. The play was a success on campus, and afterwards, she discovered her passion...acting. Her junior year of college, she changed her major from business to theatre arts with an emphasis in performance. She also minored in film so that she could learn the aesthetics of film. She became president of the African Student Drama Association and was cast in The Vagina Monologues and Hamlet: Blood in the Brain on campus. In the summer of 2008 she was cast in The Body Washer at Compass Theatre in San Diego. After graduating college in December of 2008, she was cast in her first professional theatre show Bulrusher, at New Village Arts Theatre in Carlsbad. Outside of working with Don’t Even Tripp Asia is actively pursuing her career in acting in Chicago,IL.\r\n\r\n<b>Arielle Vaughan, Director of Community Engagement/Creative Aide to Executive Director</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Damon Hastings, Director of Artistic Design</b>\r\n\r\nDo you want to work with Don’t Even Tripp? Please email donteventripp@gmail.com to inquire about positions/volunteer work!','Meet the Team','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-v1','','','2014-11-24 23:02:47','2014-11-24 23:02:47','',6,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=37',0,'revision','',0),
	(4,3,'2014-08-22 03:47:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Founded in early 2009, Don\'t Even Tripp Productions is a theatrical production company that was established by Writer/Director/Educator Ayasha J. Tripp. After receiving her B.S. in Film &amp; New Media at San Diego State University, Tripp banded together with close friends (Arielle Vaughan &amp; Asia Jackson) to establish an organization that would present powerful new works that people of diverse backgrounds could connect with. We were inspired to shed led light on topics that were current yet not being discussed in theatre.\r\n\r\nOur core belief system as an organization is to go beyond the expected and portray a variety of stories that speak personally to individual backgrounds. We make theatre accessible for today’s modern generation. Our productions challenge societal norms, and bring into question issues regarding race, religion, education, politics, etc. We entertain, but more importantly we educate and empower. The goal is to create theatre that will spark dialogue and motivate people to think critically. We use theatre as a means to bring the community together.\r\n\r\nReason behind the name:\r\n\r\nOutside of the fact that the name of the company embodies the family name, Tripp, one of the reasons we decided to name the company Don\'t Even Tripp was to reflect our perspective and attitude towards the challenges of producing quality theatre that may come our way. Meaning, despite what challenges or barriers we are presented with, we refuse to succumb to the pressure or setbacks of life. In our culture, to trip, is to worry and have anxiety over something. Therefore, Don\'t Even Tripp... don’t even worry about it! We will conquer, prevail, and always provide 100% effort in what we present. With enough faith, persistence, and commitment to the organization and community, we believe we can overcome any obstacle that may come our way.\r\n\r\nIf you like what you see, please do not hesitate to contact us! We are a creative group of open- minded, and loving people who have an extreme passion for theatre, film and the arts! Thanks for checking us out and we look forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nMuch Love,\r\n\r\nthe Don\'t Even Tripp team','About Us','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-08-22 03:47:28','2014-08-22 03:47:28','',0,'http://donteventripp.com/?page_id=4',0,'page','',0),
	(30,3,'2014-08-22 03:47:28','2014-08-22 03:47:28','Founded in early 2009, Don\'t Even Tripp Productions is a theatrical production company that was established by Writer/Director/Educator Ayasha J. Tripp. After receiving her B.S. in Film &amp; New Media at San Diego State University, Tripp banded together with close friends (Arielle Vaughan &amp; Asia Jackson) to establish an organization that would present powerful new works that people of diverse backgrounds could connect with. We were inspired to shed led light on topics that were current yet not being discussed in theatre.\r\n\r\nOur core belief system as an organization is to go beyond the expected and portray a variety of stories that speak personally to individual backgrounds. We make theatre accessible for today’s modern generation. Our productions challenge societal norms, and bring into question issues regarding race, religion, education, politics, etc. We entertain, but more importantly we educate and empower. The goal is to create theatre that will spark dialogue and motivate people to think critically. We use theatre as a means to bring the community together.\r\n\r\nReason behind the name:\r\n\r\nOutside of the fact that the name of the company embodies the family name, Tripp, one of the reasons we decided to name the company Don\'t Even Tripp was to reflect our perspective and attitude towards the challenges of producing quality theatre that may come our way. Meaning, despite what challenges or barriers we are presented with, we refuse to succumb to the pressure or setbacks of life. In our culture, to trip, is to worry and have anxiety over something. Therefore, Don\'t Even Tripp... don’t even worry about it! We will conquer, prevail, and always provide 100% effort in what we present. With enough faith, persistence, and commitment to the organization and community, we believe we can overcome any obstacle that may come our way.\r\n\r\nIf you like what you see, please do not hesitate to contact us! We are a creative group of open- minded, and loving people who have an extreme passion for theatre, film and the arts! Thanks for checking us out and we look forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nMuch Love,\r\n\r\nthe Don\'t Even Tripp team','About Us','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2014-08-22 03:47:28','2014-08-22 03:47:28','',4,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=30',0,'revision','',0),
	(20,2,'2014-08-20 03:13:15','2014-08-20 03:13:15','Founded in early 2009, Don\'t Even Tripp Productions is a theatrical production company that was established by Writer/Director/Educator Ayasha J. Tripp.  After receiving her B.S. in Film &amp; New Media at San Diego State University, Tripp banded together with close friends(Arielle Vaughan &amp; Asia Jackson) to establish an organization that would present powerful new works that people of diverse backgrounds could connect with.  We were tired of the seeing the same stories being told and wanted to shed led light on topics that were current but were not being discussed in theatre.\r\n\r\nOur core belief system as an organization is to go beyond the expected and portray a variety of stories that speak personally to individual backgrounds. We make theatre accessible for today’s modern generation. Our productions challenge societal norms, and bring into question issues regarding race, religion, education, politics, and etc. We entertain but more importantly we educate and empower. The goal is to create theatre that will spark dialogue and motivate people to think critically. We use theatre as a means to bring the community together.\r\n\r\nReason behind the name:\r\n\r\nOutside of the fact that the name of the company embodies the family name, Tripp, one of the reasons we decided to name the company Don\'t Even Tripp was to reflect our perspective and attitude towards the challenges of producing quality theatre that may come our way. Meaning, despite what challenges or barriers we are presented with, we are not the type of company to succumb to the pressure or setbacks of life. In our culture, to trip, is to worry and have anxiety over something. Don\'t Even Tripp basically means: Don’t even worry about it. We will conquer, prevail, and always provide a 100% in all productions we offer to our audience. With enough faith, persistence, and commitment to the company and community, we believe we can overcome any obstacle that may come our way. So basically, we\'re not worried about what is to come, we\'re ready for it and willing to give our all in what we do. We’re ready to work for you…our community\r\n\r\nIf you like what you see, please do not hesitate to contact us! We are talented group of open- minded, loving, creative people who have an extreme passion for theatre/film and the arts! Thanks for checking us out and we look forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nMuch Love,\r\n\r\nDon\'t Even Tripp Staff','About Us','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2014-08-20 03:13:15','2014-08-20 03:13:15','',4,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=20',0,'revision','',0),
	(5,3,'2014-08-06 19:43:31','2014-08-06 19:43:31','Founded in early 2009, Don\'t Even Tripp Productions is a theatrical production company that was established by Writer/Director A.J. Tripp. Even though Miss Tripp is the founder of the company, she has banded together with a talented group of friends who are just as committed to producing meaningful works of arts. We aim to activate the mind, body and soul of our community, embodying the motto by of, <i>“Keep Calm &amp; Don’t Even Tripp.\" </i>Meaning, despite what challenges may come our way, we are determined to entertain, challenge, and empower our audience with heart felt inspiring shows that will activate the mind, body and soul of our community.\r\n\r\nDon’t Even Tripp is focused on providing our audience original productions in the areas of theatre, film, and radio.  Our core belief system as a company is to go beyond the expected and portray a variety of stories that speak personally to individuals from diverse backgrounds. We are committed to making theatre accessible to today’s modern generation and telling stories that have yet to be told. We recognize the importance of creating stories that reflect the personal experiences of individuals in society and we aim to shed light on topics that are current but not often discussed in theatre.  We believe we have the PASSION to inspire others with stories of PURPOSE that will provoke POWER and change unto ones\' life.  We aim to make sure our audience members and supporters are fed with heart-felt stories that reflect what is going on within their community. We also aim to provide solutions through our productions in the hopes of provoking discourse that will eventually motivate people to change the world in which we live in today. In a nutshell, we are not just aiming to entertain our audience…we are aiming to <i>empower </i>them.\r\n\r\nReason behind the name:\r\n\r\nOutside of the fact that the name of the company embodies my family name, Tripp, one of the reasons we decided to name the company Don\'t Even Tripp was to reflect our perspective and attitude towards the challenges of producing quality theatre that may come our way. Meaning, despite what challenges or barriers we are presented with, we are not the type of company to succumb to the pressure or setbacks of life. In our culture, to trip, is to worry and have anxiety over something. Don\'t Even Tripp basically means: Don’t even worry about it. We will conquer, prevail, and always provide a 100% in all productions we offer to our audience. With enough faith, persistence, and commitment to the company and community, we believe we can overcome any obstacle that may come our way. So basically, we\'re not worried about what is to come, we\'re ready for it and willing to give our all in what we do. We’re ready to work for you…our community\r\n\r\nIf you like what you see, please do not hesitate to contact us! We are talented group of open- minded, loving, creative people who have an extreme passion for theatre/film and the arts! Thanks for checking us out and we look forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nMuch Love,\r\n\r\nDon\'t Even Tripp Staff\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','About Us','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2014-08-06 19:43:31','2014-08-06 19:43:31','',4,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=5',0,'revision','',0),
	(6,3,'2014-11-24 23:02:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<b>Ayasha J. Tripp, Executive Director/Founder</b>\r\n\r\nAyasha  is an energetic and passionate young woman who comes from the small town of Pittsburg, CA – the outskirts of the bustling San Francisco Bay Area. She\'s been writing stories since she was 7. Her passion and love for writing, film and theatre led her to pursue a degree in Television/Film New Media from San Diego State University. In her four and half years of attending SDSU she had the opportunity to study abroad in Singapore at Nanyang Technological University and study new media and film. She has written and directed two short films entitled, \'Unidentified\' and \'Bowling from Behind.\' In her last year attending SDSU, in association with the African American Student Drama Association she was granted the opportunity to produce/direct/write her first full length 3-Act play entitled, \'The Skin I’m In.\' The play was a huge success on her campus and sparked the idea for her to create Don\'t Even Tripp Productions. In the spring of 2010, her newly founded production company released her 2nd full length play \'and an Angel Came Down\' which premiered at the Lesher Center for the Arts in Walnut Creek, CA. The play was received very well, selling out the 2nd night! Half of the ticket proceeds were donated to the Youth Uprising Center of Oakland, CA.  After the production Tripp relocated to Chicago to expand her knowledge on theatre and writing. She had the opportunity to work as a Development Associate at the Writers Theatre. She was also under the mentorship of playwright Gloria Bond Clunie and Director  Chuck Smith and was granted the opportunity to work as their stage manager for the stage reading for the play <em>Smoke. </em>Ayasha has just recently graduated with her Masters in Afro American Studies  from the University of Wisconsin Madison. During her time on campus she worked closely with Patrick Sims founder of TCSA(Theatre for Culture &amp; Social Awareness) and hosted the WSUM radio show\"The Velvet Rope Radio Hour\" She has the opportunity to teach creative writing and theatre at UW Madison, Writers in Prison Project, and UC Berkeley Upward Bound Program. She is now back home in the Bay Area and is beyond ready to take Don\'t Even Tripp to the next level. \"I just want to help people tap into their purpose and passion and I believe theatre that can do that\"!\r\n\r\n<b>Asia Jackson, Literary Manager</b>\r\n\r\nAsia Jackson is an actress and avid lover of theatre who is also  from the Bay Area, CA. Upon entering college at San Diego State, she, like so many prospective and freshman college students, did not know what she wanted to do. She pre-majored in business with an emphasis in management. However, her sophomore year, she randomly auditioned in a student-written play, and was cast as the lead. The play was a success on campus, and afterwards, she discovered her passion...acting. Her junior year of college, she changed her major from business to theatre arts with an emphasis in performance. She also minored in film so that she could learn the aesthetics of film. She became president of the African Student Drama Association and was cast in The Vagina Monologues and Hamlet: Blood in the Brain on campus. In the summer of 2008 she was cast in The Body Washer at Compass Theatre in San Diego. After graduating college in December of 2008, she was cast in her first professional theatre show Bulrusher, at New Village Arts Theatre in Carlsbad. Outside of working with Don’t Even Tripp Asia is actively pursuing her career in acting in Chicago,IL.\r\n\r\n<b>Arielle Vaughan, Director of Community Engagement/Creative Aide to Executive Director</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Damon Hastings, Director of Artistic Design</b>\r\n\r\nDo you want to work with Don’t Even Tripp? Please email donteventripp@gmail.com to inquire about positions/volunteer work!','Meet the Team','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-11-24 23:02:47','2014-11-24 23:02:47','',0,'http://donteventripp.com/?page_id=6',0,'page','',0),
	(7,3,'2014-08-06 19:45:08','2014-08-06 19:45:08','<b>Page 2: The Company(The crew)</b>\r\n\r\n<b>A.J. (Executive Director/Founder)</b>\r\n\r\nAJ. is an energetic and passionate young woman who comes from the small town of Pittsburg, CA – the outskirts of the bustling San Francisco Bay Area. Her passion/love for writing, film and theatre made her decide to pursue a degree in Television/Film New Media from San Diego State University. In her four and half years of attending SDSU she had the opportunity to study abroad in Singapore at Nanyang Technological University and study new media and film. She has written/directed two short films entitled, \'Unidentified\' and \'Bowling from Behind.\' In her last year attending SDSU, in association with the African American Student Drama Association she was granted the opportunity to produce/direct/write her first full length 3-Act play entitled, \'The Skin I’m In.\' The play was a huge success on her campus and sparked the idea for her to create Don\'t Even Tripp Productions. In the spring of 2010, her newly founded production company released her 2nd full length play \'and an Angel Came Down\' which premiered at the Lesher Center for the Arts in Walnut Creek, CA. The play was received very well, selling out the 2nd night! Half of the ticket proceeds were donated to the Youth Uprising Center of Oakland, CA. Set to graduate this Spring, Ayasha is an M.A. candidate for Afro American Studies at University of Wisconsin Madison and also plays host of the Velvet Rope Radio Hour on campus. She aspires to assist young people find their passion/purpose in this world through the use of arts and writing.\r\n\r\n<b>Asia Jackson (Director of Production)</b>\r\n\r\nAsia Jackson is an actress and avid lover of theatre who is also the from the Bay Area, CA. Upon entering college at San Diego State, she, like so many prospective and freshman college students, did not know what she wanted to do. She pre-majored in business with an emphasis in management. However, her sophomore year, she randomly auditioned in a student-written play, and was cast as the lead. The play was a success on campus, and afterwards, she discovered her passion...acting. Her junior year of college, she changed her major from business to theatre arts with an emphasis in performance. She also minored in film so that she could learn the aesthetics of film. She became president of the African Student Drama Association and was cast in The Vagina Monologues and Hamlet: Blood in the Brain on campus. In the summer of 2008 she was cast in The Body Washer at Compass Theatre in San Diego. After graduating college in December of 2008, she was cast in her first professional theatre show Bulrusher, at New Village Arts Theatre in Carlsbad. Outside of working with Don’t Even Tripp Asia is actively pursuing her career in acting in Chicago,IL.\r\n\r\n<b>Arielle Vaughan Director of Marketing/Public Relations</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Damon Hastings Director of Artistic Design</b>\r\n\r\nDo you want to work with Don’t Even Tripp? Please email donteventripp@gmail.com to inquire about positions/volunteer work!','The Crew','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-v1','','','2014-08-06 19:45:08','2014-08-06 19:45:08','',6,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=7',0,'revision','',0),
	(8,3,'2014-08-22 04:48:42','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<em><strong>\"The Skin I’m In\"</strong></em>\r\n\r\n-Production Date: April 18th, 2008\r\n\r\n-Premier Location: Experimental Theatre - San Diego State University\r\n\r\n-Writer/Director: Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n-Synopsis: A story set in the early ‘90’s centering around two young African American girls from two different worlds. One from the mean streets of  Compton, CA - the other who is from the sheltered areas of Beverly Hills who has white adoptive parents. This comedy/drama focuses on issues of race, identity, acceptance, and unity.\r\n\r\n<b><i>“and an Angel Came Down”</i></b>\r\n\r\n<b>Production Date: </b>April 23rd &amp; 24th, 2010\r\n\r\n<b>Premier Location: </b>Lesher Center for the Arts - Walnut Creek, CA\r\n\r\n<b>Writer/Director: </b>Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n<b>Synopsis: </b>The story of young man who is dealing with the murder of his younger sister, and even though he claims to be at peace and received spiritual healing through God, in reality he is masking with his pain with an addiction to pain killers. The play would be categorized as a drama, with a great deal of comic relief. It will bring to the audience’s attention issues of dealing with forgiveness, confronting past problems, and most importantly, addressing the issue of not just talking in our faith but instead, walking in it.\r\n\r\n<b>Link for the playbill:</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram\">http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Past Productions','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-08-22 04:48:42','2014-08-22 04:48:42','',0,'http://donteventripp.com/?page_id=8',0,'page','',0),
	(21,2,'2014-08-20 03:16:20','2014-08-20 03:16:20','The Skin I’m In\r\n\r\n-Production Date: April 18th 2008\r\n\r\n-Premier Location: Experimental Theatre, San Diego State University\r\n\r\n-Writer/Director: Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n-Synopsis: A story set in the early ‘90’s centering around two young African American girls from two different worlds. One from the mean streets of  Compton, CA - the other who is from the sheltered areas of Beverly Hills who has white adoptive parents. This comedy/drama focuses on issues of race, identity, acceptance, and unity.\r\n\r\n<b><i>“and an Angel Came Down”</i></b>\r\n\r\n<b>Production Date: </b>April 23rd &amp; 24th\r\n\r\n<b>Premier Location: </b>Lesher Center for the Arts\r\n\r\nWalnut Creek, CA\r\n\r\n<b>Writer/Director: </b>Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n<b>Synopsis: </b>The story of young man who is dealing with the murder of his younger sister, and even though he claims to be at peace and received spiritual healing through God, in reality he is masking with his pain with an addiction to pain killers. The play would be categorized as a drama, with a great deal of comic relief. It will bring to the audience’s attention issues of dealing with forgiveness, confronting past problems, and most importantly, addressing the issue of not just talking in our faith but instead, walking in it.\r\n\r\n<b>Link for the playbill:</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram\">http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Past Productions','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2014-08-20 03:16:20','2014-08-20 03:16:20','',8,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=21',0,'revision','',0),
	(9,3,'2014-08-06 19:46:07','2014-08-06 19:46:07','The Skin I’m In\r\n\r\n-Production Date: April 18th 2008\r\n\r\n-Premier Location: Experimental Theatre, San Diego State University\r\n\r\n-Writer/Director: Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n-Synopsis: A story set in the early ‘90’s centering around two young African American girls from two different worlds. One from the mean streets of  Compton, CA - the other who is from the sheltered areas of Beverly Hills who has white adoptive parents. This comedy/drama focuses on issues of race, identity, acceptance, and unity.\r\n\r\n<b><i>“and an Angel Came Down”</i></b>\r\n\r\n<b>Production Date: </b>April 23rd &amp; 24th\r\n\r\n<b>Premier Location: </b>Lesher Center for the Arts\r\n\r\nWalnut Creek, CA\r\n\r\n<b>Writer/Director: </b>Ayasha Tripp\r\n\r\n<b>Synopsis: </b>The story of young man who is dealing with the murder of his younger sister, and even though he claims to be at peace and received spiritual healing through God, in reality he is masking with his pain with an addiction to pain killers. The play would be categorized as a drama, with a great deal of comic relief. It will bring to the audience’s attention issues of dealing with forgiveness, confronting past problems, and most importantly, addressing the issue of not just talking in our faith but instead, walking in it.\r\n\r\n<b>Link for the playbill:</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram\">http://issuu.com/oneofonedesign/docs/angelprogram</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Page 4: Velvet Rope Radio Hour</b>\r\n\r\nDon’t Even Tripp productions present to you The Velvet Rope Radio Hour.  We go live on WSUM 91.7FM Madison Radio every Wednesday 9am to 10:30am. We discuss all of the latest news in entertainment, pop culture and sports! You can stream us live here:\r\n\r\nhttp://wsum.org/player/\r\n\r\nThis season on the Velvet Rope Radio Hour we’ll be introducing our first ever Radio Dramas entitled “Blurred Lines.” These short 8-10 minute dramas highlight social and political issues going on in society.\r\n\r\nIf you can’t listen to us live! Don’t Tripp, we got this! Our shows and radio dramas are will be available via itunes podcasts.\r\n\r\nBLURRED LINES\r\n\r\nOur first radio drama entitled: <b>\"Whose Rights\"</b> Here is the blurb about the story.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b><i>The issue of Women’s rights is something that is constantly being discussed throughout our media and culture. However, how much of the dialogue concerning Women’s right also includes men? Should men be considered a factor in regards to Women’s rights or are these issues solely left for women to discuss and defend? </i></b>\r\n\r\n<b><i>In this Radio Drama entitled, “Whose Rights?” we meet the couple Arthur and LaToya. Listen to their story and decide for yourself who has the right to make the decision on their circumstance.</i></b>\r\n\r\nOur show goes live every Wednesday 10am to 11am. WSUM 91.7FM You can stream us live from this link: <a href=\"http://wsum.org/player/\">http://wsum.org/player/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Past Productions','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2014-08-06 19:46:07','2014-08-06 19:46:07','',8,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=9',0,'revision','',0),
	(10,3,'2014-08-22 05:22:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Don’t Even Tripp Production is in the process of setting up its Board of Trustees. Are you not only an avid fan but supporter of theatre and are looking to contribute to Don’t Even Tripp’s ongoing success?\r\n\r\nContact us at <em>community@donteventripp.com</em> for more information on joining our board!\r\n\r\nUpcoming Project:\r\n\r\nOur next original production, \"Generation of Dreams\" coming to you Spring 2015! Be on the lookout for specific dates, locations and ticket information as well as an upcoming production blog so you can hear about the step-by-step process of what goes down behind the scenes with Don\'t Even Tripp.','Updates','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-08-22 05:22:28','2014-08-22 05:22:28','',0,'http://donteventripp.com/?page_id=10',0,'page','',0),
	(11,3,'2014-08-06 19:51:48','2014-08-06 19:51:48','Don’t Even Tripp Production is in the process of setting up its Board of Trustees. Are you not only an avid fan but supporter of theatre and are looking to contribute to Don’t Even Tripp’s ongoing success? Contact us at donteventripp@gmail.com for more information how to join our exciting new board!\r\n\r\nUpcoming Projects:\r\n\r\nOur next original production, \"Generation of Dreams\" coming to you Spring 2015! Be on the lookout for specific dates, locations and ticket information. as well as our production blog so you can hear about the step by step process of what goes down behind the scenes with Don\'t Even Tripp.','Updates','','inherit','open','open','','10-revision-v1','','','2014-08-06 19:51:48','2014-08-06 19:51:48','',10,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=11',0,'revision','',0),
