	(25,2,'2014-08-20 03:38:42','2014-08-20 03:38:42','<b>Page 2: The Company(The crew)</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Ayasha J. Tripp (Executive Director/Founder)</b>\r\n\r\nAyasha  is an energetic and passionate young woman who comes from the small town of Pittsburg, CA – the outskirts of the bustling San Francisco Bay Area. She\'s been writing stories since she was 7. Her passion/love for writing, film and theatre led her to pursue a degree in Television/Film New Media from San Diego State University. In her four and half years of attending SDSU she had the opportunity to study abroad in Singapore at Nanyang Technological University and study new media and film. She has written/directed two short films entitled, \'Unidentified\' and \'Bowling from Behind.\' In her last year attending SDSU, in association with the African American Student Drama Association she was granted the opportunity to produce/direct/write her first full length 3-Act play entitled, \'The Skin I’m In.\' The play was a huge success on her campus and sparked the idea for her to create Don\'t Even Tripp Productions. In the spring of 2010, her newly founded production company released her 2nd full length play \'and an Angel Came Down\' which premiered at the Lesher Center for the Arts in Walnut Creek, CA. The play was received very well, selling out the 2nd night! Half of the ticket proceeds were donated to the Youth Uprising Center of Oakland, CA.  After the production Tripp relocated to Chicago to expand her knowledge on theatre and writing. She had the opportunity to work as a Development Associate at the Writers Theatre. She was also under the mentorship of playwright Gloria Bond Clunie and Director  Chuck Smith and was granted the opportunity to work as their stage manager for the stage reading for the play <em>Smoke. </em>Ayasha has just recently graduated with her Masters in Afro American Studies  from the University of Wisconsin Madison. During her time on campus she worked closely with Patrick Sims founder of TCSA(Theatre for Culture &amp; Social Awareness) and hosted the WSUM radio show\"The Velvet Rope Radio Hour\" She has the opportunity to teach creative writing and theatre at UW Madison, Writers in Prison Project, and UC Berkeley Upward Bound Program. She is now back home in the Bay Area and is beyond ready to take Don\'t Even Tripp to the next level. \"I just want to help people tap into their purpose and passion and I believe theatre that can do that\"!\r\n\r\n<b>Asia Jackson (Literary Manager)</b>\r\n\r\nAsia Jackson is an actress and avid lover of theatre who is also  from the Bay Area, CA. Upon entering college at San Diego State, she, like so many prospective and freshman college students, did not know what she wanted to do. She pre-majored in business with an emphasis in management. However, her sophomore year, she randomly auditioned in a student-written play, and was cast as the lead. The play was a success on campus, and afterwards, she discovered her passion...acting. Her junior year of college, she changed her major from business to theatre arts with an emphasis in performance. She also minored in film so that she could learn the aesthetics of film. She became president of the African Student Drama Association and was cast in The Vagina Monologues and Hamlet: Blood in the Brain on campus. In the summer of 2008 she was cast in The Body Washer at Compass Theatre in San Diego. After graduating college in December of 2008, she was cast in her first professional theatre show Bulrusher, at New Village Arts Theatre in Carlsbad. Outside of working with Don’t Even Tripp Asia is actively pursuing her career in acting in Chicago,IL.\r\n\r\n<b>Arielle Vaughan Director of Marketing/Public Relations</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Damon Hastings Director of Artistic Design</b>\r\n\r\nDo you want to work with Don’t Even Tripp? Please email donteventripp@gmail.com to inquire about positions/volunteer work!','Meet the Team','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-v1','','','2014-08-20 03:38:42','2014-08-20 03:38:42','',6,'http://donteventripp.com/?p=25',0,'revision','',0),
